00:01:43.350 --> 00:01:47.920
The number of molecules in a fixed volume
of gas, like the volume of air in your lungs,

00:01:47.920 --> 00:01:52.780
does not change with the type of gas (assuming
the pressures are reasonably low).

00:01:52.780 --> 00:01:57.170
As long as the temperature and the pressure
are the same, it does not matter whether it

00:01:57.170 --> 00:02:01.610
is helium or air, the number of molecules
is the same.

00:02:01.610 --> 00:02:05.630
The mass of those molecules is then measured
by atomic weight.

00:02:05.630 --> 00:02:10.149
Atomic weight is a dimensionless physical
quantity (which is why it works so well for

00:02:10.149 --> 00:02:13.110
a gas that does not necessarily have a given
dimension).

00:02:13.110 --> 00:02:18.969
It is the ratio of the average mass of atoms
of an element compared to 1/12 of the mass

00:02:18.969 --> 00:02:20.999
of an atom of carbon-12.

00:02:20.999 --> 00:02:25.109
All that basically means is the higher the
number the heavier the gas.

00:02:25.109 --> 00:02:27.810
Helium has an atomic weight of 4.002602.

00:02:27.810 --> 00:02:33.819
Air which is approximately 80% Nitrogen, has
differing characteristics depending on the

00:02:33.819 --> 00:02:34.819
environment.

00:02:34.819 --> 00:02:39.890
(for instance if you live in Los Angeles its
about 99.27% car exhaust) ðŸ˜‰ Because of

