00:02:47.849 --> 00:02:51.239
So why the perceived difference in your voice
with helium?

00:02:51.239 --> 00:02:55.329
The answer lies in how sound waves travel
through a given gas.

00:02:55.329 --> 00:02:59.720
The more dense, or heavier, the gas, the slower
the sound wave will travel.

00:02:59.720 --> 00:03:01.569
Helium is much lighter than air.

00:03:01.569 --> 00:03:05.170
The speed of a sound wave through helium will
then be much higher.

00:03:05.170 --> 00:03:10.310
So by inhaling helium and using it as the
source of the perceived sound, you are simply

00:03:10.310 --> 00:03:13.430
increasing the speed or frequency of your
voice.

00:03:13.430 --> 00:03:18.150
You are not changing the pitch, since your
vocal chords are vibrating at the same speed

00:03:18.150 --> 00:03:19.530
as when you are using air.

00:03:19.530 --> 00:03:23.790
You are also not changing the configuration
of your vocal tract.

00:03:23.790 --> 00:03:28.270
So while the base frequency of the chords
remains the same, the frequency of the sound

00:03:28.270 --> 00:03:33.529
heard by others is increased due to the wave
traveling through helium much faster than

00:03:33.529 --> 00:03:51.340
through air.

